article.description:
Cappie Pondexter scored 23 points to lead the
Phoenix Mercury past Chicago 90-77 Sunday night, handing the
expansion Sky its league-record 13th straight loss.
article.headline: Mercury hand Sky league-record 13th straight loss
article.linkText: Mercury hand Sky league-record 13th straight loss
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury showed what they can do when
their running style works.

Cappie Pondexter scored 23 points in 29 minutes to lead Phoenix
past Chicago 90-77 Sunday night, handing the expansion Sky their
league-record 13th straight loss.

Chicago (1-13) tied the single-season mark set by Detroit in
2002.

"It's getting there," said Kelly Miller, who added 12 points
and seven assists in 20 minutes for the Mercury. "I think we know
each other a little bit better now so it's easier to try and get
into that flow, the run-and-gun thing. But it's fun. It's the way I
like to play."

Pondexter, the third-leading scorer in the WNBA, was 4-of-6 from
3-point range in the third quarter for Phoenix (5-7) after the Sky
cut the Mercury's 14-point halftime lead to nine. Phoenix, the
highest scoring team in the league, led by as many as 24 points in
the second half.

"We didn't have an answer for them," Chicago coach Dave Cowens
said. "They went inside-out and took the ball out of our point
guard's hands. We tried to make some adjustments, but that slowed
us down a little bit. They just outplayed us tonight."

Phoenix had 22 assists on 32 baskets and forced 14 Sky
turnovers. The Mercury outshot and outrebounded Chicago, which
led only once, 2-0.

"We are trying to demonstrate that we are on the climb and on
the improve, going up and up, every win is important," Phoenix
coach Paul Westhead said.

Miller, acquired in the offseason, was expected to be the
catalyst for Westhead's new high-octane offense but missed three
weeks with a partially torn right hamstring.

Chicago rookie Candice Dupree scored 15 points, all in the first
half.

"We had some runs and coach went smaller in the second half to
try to run the floor a little bit," Dupree said. "I thought we
played well, just didn't have enough to overcome their lead."

Bernadette Ngoyisa added 14 points and Amanda Lassiter had 13
for the Sky, who never got closer than nine points in the second
half.

Kamila Vodichkova added 19 points and nine rebounds and Diana
Taurasi had 14 points -- all in the first half -- and six assists for
the Mercury, who have won five of eight since losing their first
four games.

"When Kamila plays like that, we're a really good team,"
Taurasi said. "You go through some ups and downs in a long season.
This is a good win but like coach says, win or lose, it's how you
react to it."

Phoenix entered the game as the highest scoring team in the WNBA
(83.8 points) and Chicago was last (65.8).

Phoenix was 7-of-14 from beyond the 3-point line in the first
half to open up a 51-37 lead at the break. The Mercury made 11 of
27 (41 percent) for the night.

"I take no credit for that," Westhead said. "I just try to
get our players down the court quickly and try to beat the
defensive setup so they can't get all five back. They are just
gapping and helping each other."

The Mercury were 19-of-34 (56 percent) from the field in the
first 20 minutes and finished the game with a 40-26 advantage in
rebounds.
